## Executive Summary

Mastercard Foundation stands out as a strategically important donor with
a strong preference for large, targeted funding disbursements averaging
\$7.5 million per transaction but fewer transactions annually than
peers. In 2025, it allocated \$313 million primarily toward global
programs, showing significant regional funding disparities and a high
earmarking rate (~37.5%), exceeding other donors. The Foundation has
steadily expanded its reach, supporting an increasing number of
countries from 8 to 11 between 2022 and 2025, signaling growing
geographic diversification. Its funding is volatile yet impactful,
favoring strategic, sizable investments that align with focused
interventions—key considerations for proposal design and fundraising
efforts.

## Volatility

This visualization tracks Mastercard Foundation’s funding transactions
from June 2024 to September 2025, highlighting significant volatility in
transaction values. The average transaction amount is 7.5 million USD,
markedly higher than the benchmark top 10 donors’ average of 2.7 million
USD. However, Mastercard Foundation completes far fewer transactions per
year, averaging 22.5 compared to 376 by other donors. This indicates a
funding model concentrated in larger, less frequent disbursements versus
smaller, more regular contributions common among peers. The transaction
values vary widely, with a median of approximately 785,568 USD and an
extreme maximum nearing 296 million USD, demonstrating peaks of
substantial funding. For proposal writers, this pattern suggests
focusing on interventions that require sizeable, periodic infusions of
funds and planning program milestones accordingly. Fundraising
strategies should emphasize the impact of large-scale investments but
also consider diversification to increase transaction frequency and
reduce potential cash flow risks. Overall, this funding profile reflects
a strategic donor approach favoring substantial, targeted transactions
over frequent smaller payments, impacting operational planning and
partner coordination.
